cp||at|Although Marty's style of playing that 3@c is not forcing is a reasonable one, this is one area where there are no standards and you must have a partnership agreement.|
at|^^|cp||at|^b|
at|^^|cp||at|^bFor example, those players who use Lebensohl (a very complicated convention which I don't recommend for most players) would play that 3@c is forcing (as are all 3-level bids). If they want to stop in 3C, they would bid 2NT which forces a 3C bid by opener. They can then pass or correct to whatever suit they want to play in.|
at|^^|cp||at|^b|
at|^^|cp||at|^bOther players might decide that 3@c is forcing and give up the ability to stop in a partial at the 3-level.|
at|^^|cp||at|^b|
at|^^|cp||at|^bStill another alternative is to play that 3 of a minor is not forcing but 3@h is forcing. The idea behind that style is that you want to be able to compete when you hold a minor suit (since it is unlikely that you can make 5 of a minor) but, when you hold a major, you want to have the ability to investigate whether 3NT or 4 of your major is the best spot.|
at|^^|cp||at|^b|
at|^^|cp||at|^bPersonally, I would recommend that most players play 3-level bids as forcing (and play "systems on/stolen bid doubles" in general when the opponents compete over a 1NT opener).|
